    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="180"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d180">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/985½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">20 January, 1918</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: The suggestion made by the
                    Japanese government in this despatch<note n="33" xml:id="d180fn1">Telegram of
                        Jan. 17, 1918, from the Ambassador in Japan, <ref
                            target="frus1918Russiav02#pg_29">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1918, Russia, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 29</ref>.</note> seems to me very
                    significant of possible coming events, and I would be very much obliged to you
                    if you would tell me what reply you think should be made to it.</p>
                <p>The fact that the Japanese are sending a larger naval force to Vladivostok than
                    they at first led us to expect makes an uncomfortable impression on me,
                    particularly in view of this latest request.</p>
                <p>It seems to me clear that we should show very clearly in our reply that we should
                    look upon military action in that quarter with distinct disapproval.</p>
                <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
